[{"id":31286,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Practical Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Nessler's reagent is an aqueous solution of potassium iodide, mercuric chloride, and potassium hydroxide. Its chemical formula is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>HgI</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>. It is used to detect the presence of ammonia. It turns into a pale brown colour in the presence of ammonia.</p><p>Nessler’s Reagent Reaction:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><munder><munder><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>HgI</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></mrow><mo>⏟</mo></munder><mrow><mi>Nessler</mi><mo>'</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo> </mo><mi>reagent</mi></mrow></munder><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>KOH</mi><mover><mo>→</mo><mrow></mrow></mover><munder><munder><mrow><mi>HgO</mi><mo>.</mo><mi>Hg</mi><mfenced><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mrow><mo>⏟</mo></munder><mrow><mi>Iodide</mi><mo> </mo><mi>of</mi><mo> </mo><mi>Millon</mi><mo>'</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo> </mo><mi>base</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>brown</mi><mo> </mo><mi>precipitate</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow></munder><mo>+</mo><mn>7</mn><mi>KI</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31299,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Practical Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Al</mi><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Fe</mi><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math> sulphides hydrolyse in water. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Ni</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Zn</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math> require basic medium with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></math> to form precipitate.&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Ca</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Ba</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math> sulphides are&nbsp;also soluble.&nbsp; only&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Cu</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;can form the precipitate with&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></math>&nbsp;in the acidic medium.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31293,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Practical Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></msubsup></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/dc0f34a4-fb3e-418a-bc95-48fb8c2b8bc6-image.png\" style=\"width: 342px; height: 70px;\" /></p><p>A white precipitate was formed when <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>BaCl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;when added to water extract of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi>SO</mi><mn>3</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup></math>&nbsp;salt. which is an&nbsp;inorganic salt.<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>white</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>pracipitate</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>BaSO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;is formed.&nbsp;Further,&nbsp;a gas <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;with burning sulphur like&nbsp;odour will be released&nbsp;when the<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>BaSO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;is&nbsp; dissolved in&nbsp;dilute HCI.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31268,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Practical Chemistry","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{X}=\\mathrm{NH}_3$ and $\\mathrm{Y}=\\mathrm{HgO}$","$\\mathrm{X}=\\mathrm{NH}_3$ and $\\mathrm{Y}=\\mathrm{K}_2 \\mathrm{HgI}_4+\\mathrm{KOH}$","$\\mathrm{X}=\\mathrm{NH}_4 \\mathrm{Cl}$ and $\\mathrm{Y}=\\mathrm{KOH}$","$\\mathrm{X}=\\mathrm{HCl}$ and $\\mathrm{Y}=\\mathrm{NH}_4 \\mathrm{Cl}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"$\\mathrm{NH}_4^{+}+\\mathrm{NaOH} \\longrightarrow \\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O}+\\mathrm{NH}_3 \\uparrow$<br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/zlgVoLdTpziORH65aQ1uy2tTAdVeTZrPImGlJs1cJ0o.original.fullsize.png\"/><br />$\\mathrm{NH}_3$ is identify by $\\mathrm{K}_2\\left[\\mathrm{HgI}_4\\right]+\\mathrm{KOH}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (7 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31300,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Practical Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Match list :-&nbsp;</p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" style=\"width: 500px;\">\t<tbody>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>(a)</td>\t\t\t<td>Lassaigne&#39;s Test</td>\t\t\t<td>(i)</td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></math>&nbsp;and Halogen</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>(b)</td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Cu</mi><mfenced><mi>II</mi></mfenced></math> Oxide</td>\t\t\t<td>(ii)</td>\t\t\t<td>Carbon</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>(c)</td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>AgNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></td>\t\t\t<td>(iii)</td>\t\t\t<td>Halogen specifically.</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>(d)</td>\t\t\t<td>Sodium fusion extract given black precipitate with acetic acid and lead acetate&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>/</mo><msub><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>COO</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Pb</mi></mrow></mfenced></math></td>\t\t\t<td>(iv)</td>\t\t\t<td>Sulphur</td>\t\t</tr>\t</tbody></table>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (16 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31285,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Practical Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>AgCN</mi></math> is soluble in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","Silver halides are soluble in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Ag</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></math> is soluble in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Na</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaCN</mi></math> are decomposed by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">The Lassaigne’s extract is first boiled with dil. HNO<sub>3</sub> to decompose cyanide or sulphide of sodium (NaCN or Na<sub>2</sub>S) formed during Lassaigne’s test. These ions would otherwise interfere with silver nitrate test for halogen.</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaCN</mi><mo> </mo><mo>(</mo><mo> </mo><mi>aq</mi><mo> </mo><mo>)</mo><mo> </mo><mo>+</mo><mo> </mo><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo> </mo><mo>(</mo><mo> </mo><mi>aq</mi><mo> </mo><mo>)</mo><mo> </mo><mo>→</mo><mo> </mo><msub><mi>NaNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo> </mo><mo>(</mo><mo> </mo><mi>aq</mi><mo> </mo><mo>)</mo><mo> </mo><mo>+</mo><mo> </mo><mi>HCN</mi><mo> </mo><mo>(</mo><mo>↑</mo><mo>)</mo></math></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Na</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mo> </mo><mo>(</mo><mo> </mo><mi>aq</mi><mo> </mo><mo>)</mo><mo> </mo><mo>+</mo><mo> </mo><mn>2</mn><mo> </mo><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo> </mo><mo>(</mo><mo> </mo><mi>aq</mi><mo> </mo><mo>)</mo><mo> </mo><mo>→</mo><mo> </mo><mn>2</mn><mo> </mo><msub><mi>NaNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo> </mo><mo>(</mo><mo> </mo><mi>aq</mi><mo> </mo><mo>)</mo><mo> </mo><mo>+</mo><mo> </mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mo> </mo><mo>(</mo><mo> </mo><mo>↑</mo><mo> </mo><mo>)</mo></math></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Hence option D is the answer.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (30 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31291,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Practical Chemistry","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Both Statement I and Statement II are true","Statement I is false but Statement II is true","Statement I is true but Statement II is false"],"answer":0,"solution":"Upon heating a borax bead dipped in cupric sulphate in a luminous flame, the colour of the bead becomes blue. Blue colour is observed due to copper (II) metaborate while copper (I) is colourless,","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (31 Jan Shift 2)","image":null}]